    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1917-05-10T10:41:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1917-05-10T10:41:00-05:00" n="241"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d241">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 600.119/61</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in the Netherlands</hi> (<persName
                        corresp="frus1917Supp02v01#p_LM1" type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Langhorne</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">The Hague</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1917-05-10T17:00:00+01:19">
                            <hi rend="italic">May 10, 1917, 5 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received 6.05 p.m.</hi>]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>906. The Minister for Foreign Affairs informed me in a conversation to-day that a
                    great deal of uneasiness is being expressed <pb facs="0364" n="1118"
                        xml:id="pg_1118"/> in Holland in connection with the reports regarding the
                    possibility that the United States will place an embargo on the shipment of
                    foodstuffs to neutral countries adjacent to Germany. He stated that he has been
                    approached by members of the Netherlands Government with a view to taking up
                    this question with the Government of the United States but that he invariably
                    replied that he did not consider this step necessary as he had entire confidence
                    in the assurances given to the Dutch Minister at Washington by the President in
                    a recent interview.</p>
                <p>An official statement of this interview was given by the Foreign Office to the
                    Dutch press on April 23 and was reported to the Department in my despatch No.
                    918 April 27.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="frus1917Supp02v01#p_LM1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Langhorne</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
